text: â€œthe last time i was here, grandpa, my sister and i were walking back over there toward the woods and witnessed a massive drug deal. it was the only time iâ€™ve ever been really frightened by strangers. we were minding our own business, but these creeps kept staring at us. it really freaked me out, especially when one of the guys followed us back down the hill after we left. i will always remember that. he was in a sports coupe with the license plate â€œ2wild4uâ€. as soon as we left the park, he slowly drove behind us all the way down the hill to one of those houses down there. it made the hair on the back of my neck stand up, and i couldnâ€™t sleep for weeks. i was afraid that someone was going to come find me,â€ i said, retelling my story without much thought. â€œyou were here with your grandpa and your sister? what were you wearing?â€ â€œwhat does that have to do with anything?â€ i asked, put off by the random question noah always managed to equate with sex. â€œbecause i think i was here that day. this was my park. i was in charge of distribution here and a few other places,â€ he said. -r. macceile 2018 just a few more days left for the proceeds from your purchase of candy apple butterscotch to benefit my #holidaycharityevent in support of the american foundation for suicide prevention #afspnational we are so close to our goal! you can find more info at rebeccasbookshop.com #authorsofinstagram #ptsdsurvivor #metoo #memoir #nonfiction #lastminutegiftidea

text:
this is how i wake up when i have nightmares at night. to whimsy pushing his face into my face. a dog who loves to sleep alone, he comes up and stays with me after. a dog who prefers to nap rather than follow me around (unlike his brother), he follows me out to the kitchen while i get water. after five days straight of nightmares (or i should say the same nightmare), sweet whimsy still hops up on the bed so i can wake up to him right there. and bugs, sweet bugs, is trained to wake me up and after, curls up with me under the covers. i think it is important to analyze what #ptsd gave me to not let my traumatizers hold the narrative of my trauma. and while they took sleep from me, and dignity, and bodily autonomy, and the feeling of safety at night, they gave me this moment. i am not thankful to them; i am thankful to whimsy, doggo with literal holes in his heart, who hid under the bed for the first six months i had him, who arrived to me with no hair covered in bugs and bite wounds, who chose me and not the other way around, who has also overcome trauma, who has also chosen to trust again, who showed me the path to slowly crawling out from under my own metaphorical bed and trusting the night again. sweet, sweet whimsy, how i wish i could tell you.
.
.
.

text:
you see, that's hows this thing goes sometimes. the same thing that saves you, crucifies you. and all that's left are memories that you can't even be sure are real anymore. all you have are questions. you've witnessed yourself dissolve, and you don't even know who you are anymore. maybe there are no answers. all i know is love doesn't always show up the same way, doesn't always look familiar, doesn't always survive the same way. sometimes it shows up in the dark, because it can't bare the light. i don't know why but sometimes love can always live in the shadows. there is a kind of love that's always with you, even after you were away, it's there, whispering in the dark chambers in your heart. it's never truly silent because even the dark plumes of smoke from a dying candle reminds of her hair, the way it danced around her finger as she spun it. see, it doesn't matter how love comes. what i know is that when it's gone, it hurts. and if you weren't still breathing you would swear that the pain was death itself. it's devastating.  it's like watching yourself die and having to come back and sort through the wreckage. hearts are fragile things, they break. and when they heal it's never the same way, it's never whole, never complete again. but is that it, is that all there is? the big drama that takes you up and drops you? that's a cruel tease. here's what i believe, i believe that a broken heart isn't a loss of love. a broken heart is the full blow announcement of love. that deep down desire to connect. when your heart is broken, all there is, all you feel is what you lost. the pain won't let you see beyond that. all you feel is you is agony because heart break is a powerful expression of misalignment. being emotionally off track is hard, almost impossible to see that you gain something. but the see that, you have to heal. you have to align yourself with that gain, that feeling, that knowing, that "i may be shatter to bits right now, but somewhere in me, that magic, that alive thing, is still in me. i may have to step back and cry when i have to cry. mourn when i have to mourn, but i have to heal".
2/2
~the side of youtube that made me weak~

bannon, a former adviser to u.s. president donald trump,Â said last monthÂ he intends to set up a brussels-based foundation, the movement, to advise and coordinate the continentâ€™s various right-wing parties and political groups ahead of the 2019 europe-wide ballot.

but his scheme â€œwill not succeed,â€ as the â€œinterests of the anti-establishment parties in europe are quite different,â€ alexander gauland, who leads alternative for germany (afd), said inÂ an interview with the funke media group ofÂ newspapers in germany published saturday. - i do not see any great opportunities for cooperation, said gauland. - weâ€™re not in america.

gaulandâ€™s party â€” which is part of the europe of freedom and direct democracy group in the european assembly, alongside ukip and italyâ€™s 5stars â€” takes a hardline approach to immigration and islam like a number of its far-right peers across the continent, but diverges on other issues such as economic policy and eu membership.

text:
2018 was a great year (and some not so great moments but overall amazing)
@slutornutthemovie by @kellyshowker premiered at @hotdocs_ 
i was on the cover of @nowtoronto #hotdocs pull out. #slutornut was shown at @romtoronto as part of the #metoo and the arts program. i submitted my dissertation proposal. i traveled a lot including nyc for the opening of my dear friend caralea cole #illuminatedmanuscript art exhibit. i received the #harmony award from @harmonymovement. with the film i traveled to ottawa, sudbury, montreal and winnipeg. for fun i went to florida, barbados and jamaica. 
and more good things to come in 2019!!!....
#crushinggoals #best9 #lovinglife #2019goals #goalsetting

text:
#tbtÂ Â who here uses/has used art to heal themselves?Â Â i canâ€™t believe its been 2 years since i made the body of love. this multimedia art installation asked questions concerning the body and identity in response to rape. in the body of love, i explored notions of shame, silencing, and healing through the cultivation of power and pleasure by processes of art making. through this process, i explored rebuilding myself by making art - which facilitated growth and recovery in the midst of our highly sexualized, individualistic, objectifying culture. through this work, i ask viewers to consider love as the ultimate weapon of transformation. for as long as i live, i will continue to share the power inherent in creative expression. art saved my life.

text:
for a while, i was so angry over how my innocence has been taken from me. over the past few months i have grown so much that although the abuse was a card that should never been played, itâ€™s a card that i am almost grateful it got placed into my hand. someone stripped away my interior, and i am completely renovating my new world. 
my eyes are open, my heart is more compassionate for those around me, my friendships have grown back even stronger, my creativity has burst out of me in the oddest and sometimes most painful ways. new boundaries have been set. i have a new found love for myself that i have never experienced before. 
i canâ€™t believe itâ€™s taken 23 years to love my unapologetic self. i spent 23 years worried about how other people would perceive my life. i am so grateful that this experience has taught me to quite literally 'fuck what anyone thinks', and start doing the things that bring me the most happiness. 
today is the start of my creative work series. a project that has allowed me to reinvent myself. understand the tough stuff about trauma, self-love and emotional, physical abuse and using my creativity to heal my soul.  #hearmetoo #metoo #wecandobetter #offmychest #arttherapy

the violence against women act is up for a vote tomorrow. let me say that again... the violence against women act is up for a vote tomorrow. 
today, i had the pleasure of taking part in an important special for #hln. if you missed targeted: women, then you must catch the replay. itâ€™s an important conversation exposing the culture of violence against women in this country and abroad. there is so much work, beyond the #metoo and #timesup movements, that still needs to be done to move the needle and begin seeing women as equal, valued and deserving of everyoneâ€™s protection and empowerment. when we are uplifted and encourage (hell, even if weâ€™re not) women are capable off building bridges, moving mountains and changing the landscape of society. and we must start early...with our girls and our boys. teaching them how to treat and respect one another so that as they become adults, they understand and respect consent...they understand and respect theirs and the bodies of others...they understand and respect, value and exalt women everywhere. everywhere!!!! thatâ€™s how we move the needle.
.
.
.
if you or someone you know is experiencing domestic violence, please contact the national domestic abuse hotline at 1-800-799-safe.

text:
i'm honored to announce the official launch of twft52.

when my story first wrote itself, it wasnâ€™t a straightforward retelling. it came out as poetry. like a distant constellation or a strange snarling dog, i had to see it from the side, gaze averted, in order to get close enough. 
in starting this work, it was to create a platform sharing our experiences. i needed to give us all the voice i never had. i knew some would express through art, others would simply recount events, still others would find themselves â€“ as i did â€“ surprised by the ways creativity serves us when we need it most. 
twft52 is a year-long creative healing journey for survivors of sexual assault, abuse, and related trauma, though anyone is welcome to participate. 
weâ€™ll begin sunday evening, january 6. each week, iâ€™ll post the prompt: â€œthe word for this is ______.â€ the words are abstract, selected to be non-triggering (though we all know itâ€™s not always the obvious ones that do it), randomized so iâ€™m not dictating the order of your process. 
iâ€™ll also post a few questions to spark ideas, as well as my own answer to the prompt. iâ€™m limiting myself to 52 words for each, so i can sustain the pace and not overwhelm you. (if brevity is a virtue, i do not possess it. also, my name is jess and i overuse parentheses.) continued in comments...

text_retweet: from @chenchenwrites . i echo this to anyone who is part of a privileged group that claims to be baffled but what to do and how to help. start reading. start googling. i keep hearing men proclaiming to be confused by how to date in the â€œ#metoo era.â€ if we committed to reading books and googling articles by women (and especially women of color) about feminism how to end rape culture, and sexual violence, we would find the answers we are looking for. we can follow and repost the voices of the marginalized on this very issues. but for all of this to happen, we first have to accept that there are things outside of our first-person experience that we donâ€™t have a full understanding of. and as white people, and/or men, we have to be willing to listen to and value the voices we are taught to devalue. if you only expect to learn from men and especially white men (consciously or not), we will never be able to learn about other peopleâ€™s lives, and in turn our own unexamined perspectives that we hold to be objective and unbiased. itâ€™s time to wake up.

(pt. 4) 
much of my life has been spent fighting to survive. iâ€™ve climbed from the depths of despair, from suicidal waking nightmares, from only holding on to hope, that whatever else that comes next has to be better than the hell i was in. iâ€™ve spent a great deal of time trusting that my love and joy for art and creation will be enough, that the years of hard work will show through, and make a difference.

this is all fine and well, but has resulted in a lot of injury and necessary recovery time. i am learning now how to embrace myself with softenss, how to trust that the universe wants the best for me, and how to believe, in truth, that i am loved simply for being here. itâ€™s still really hard for me to believe sometimes. that i am enough. that i will ever be good enough for anyone. but i know i have to start with being good enough for myself, and thatâ€™s... enough.

itâ€™s a beautiful feeling, to be enough just now. realizing how much now is spent on fear and anxiety. realizing how much now could be spent making something beautiful instead of worrying it wonâ€™t ever be good enough.

text:
(pt. 6) 
how pure of a diamond do i need to be shown to believe it exists in myself?

because it does. even amidst the fear, which has threatened so lately, which has held itself clasped around my throat so much lately. i choose not to choke now, because by speaking and naming those fears, they release as opposed to leaving me crippled. i will heal my right wing. i will give my body the care and love it needs to heal and realign, so i can continue to dance higher, harder, stronger, stranger. iâ€™ve spent so much of my life trying to prove iâ€™m good enough, which has resulted in overtraining, an eating disorder, body dysmorphia, whatever else in the world... and yet, i donâ€™t even know what â€˜good enoughâ€™ looks like. i donâ€™t know what â€˜perfectionâ€™ looks like.

not until realizing iâ€™m already that diamond and i am already loved and worthy because i am here. iâ€™ve been very afraid to love myself, because thereâ€™s so much darkness tooâ€” and yet, no star in the night would seem as brilliant without the darkened sky.

text:
(pt. 8) 
everyone has their own god, some just subscribe to a more mainstream religion... itâ€™s always easier to believe in anything besides yourself. itâ€™s always easier to trust someone who claims to know what theyâ€™re doing. but easier doesnâ€™t mean worthwhile or true. i aim to show that anyone can be their own highest self, by doing my best to remain true to what i believe mine to be.

my highest self? she aims to find and play the most fun game in the universe, and by doing so help create it. rework the rules you live by, and the game changes. her playing field is movement, art, words, and music. i am learning to sing, i am learning to make music, i am learning to dance. all of it is hard, but if a game is too easy, why play? the results of my play have gotten me this far, so itâ€™ll be interesting to see how much higher the levels reach.

it feels much like a fractal of growth, passed down through familial patterns and dna, the wealth and knowledge passed down, surviving as best it can. the strength my grandmother had to survive world war two, fleeing germany to come to the united states after her house was bombed down, is in me. the strength my mother had to tell her mother â€˜noâ€™. when she got pregnant and instead of getting an abortion chose to fight for me as a single mother. that strength is in me too. i honor them now by continuing to fight and speak for womenâ€™s rights and growth,  so that women will have better options than what they had to face for themselves.

text:
*trigger warning*

according to the cdcp, in 2017, 47,000 people died by means of suicide. this puts it at a 50 year peak.

and still we see it rising more every year. i'm honestly afraid to see the 2018 statistic. 
this has been my thought the last week: 
what if i could have given even one of them a place to share their story? what if they had an outlet or a person to listen or to just know that there were others out there experiencing the same types of things? 
i have the opportunity right now to do that. and i'm inviting you to come along. 
5 days. that's how many days til podcast launch day.

my audience is full of women who struggle with any and all of the uncomfortable topics people tend to avoid because they are censored or made to feel that they are struggling alone and/or that their story doesn't matter.

my purpose with this podcast is to provide a platform for these women (and men) to come together, be part of a community that understands where there are or have been, and to share their stories.

some women are just beginning their journey with these uncomfortable issues. some women are in the midst. and some have found the means to live with or overcome their situations and thrive in a life they love. 
still others are no longer with us. 
because they didn't have a place to go, a community of support, or anyone to talk to. because they thought their story wouldn't be listened to. that it didn't matter. that they didn't matter. 
so... if you have a story relating to any of the below topics and would like to share, i am inviting you to comment or message me. you are also welcome to email me at yeslifereality@gmail.com â€¢ depression
â€¢ anxiety â€¢ ptsd â€¢ rape
â€¢ domestic abuse â€¢ bullying â€¢ divorce â€¢ abortion â€¢ body image â€¢ suicide 
or 
any other sensitive issue that pertains to you.

you can choose to remain anonymous if youâ€™d like, but i want to truly make a difference in 2019 & the only way to do that is to speak up, share, and raise awareness around the issues.

this podcast will not be censored. your story will be heard. 
you are not alone. your story matters. you matter ğŸ’

#youmatter #speakup #suicideawareness

text:
#24speciesofcrane day 11, 
so sorry to jump off the grus family before exhausting it, but we just have to #stopthesuffering.

also sorry for the following post being perhaps modestly verbose, however, my #veganwarriors, the sandhill crane, often called the #ribeyeinthesky by cattle farmers, is in a dire way and #needshelp.

firstly, we have been loving the all new beyond meat spicy habanero vegan chicken burger from @awrestaurants cranked up a notch with extra mayo, hot sauce, and #organic microgreens had me thinking of going right back out again for some authentic texmex, like maybe that dorito encased in cheese and tortilla #vegan taco thing from @tacobell , those things are the real deal. yeeehaw you quieros! see, you can have a super healthy diet and remain within the @peta guidelines.

anyways, now that thats off my chest, lets talk about the antigone canadensis, better known as the #sandhillcrane. their plumage is often worn, stained and likely singed due to their habit of soaring in thermals caused by hot air rising, often compared to hawks and eagles in their efficient flight. this bird is at most #atrisk from #huntingdogs who are known to collect over 100 #birds in a single session. hunters also shoot the birds. in addition to this, even the best hunters are depositting up to 2oz of steel everytime they pull the trigger. that means an effective hunter could dump up to 5.6 kg of the metal into the farmers fields they are protecting per 100 executed grain thieves.

the sandhill crane is now extinct in indonesia and australia, including the democratic republic of gondor (drg), formerly known as new zealand until the @republicanparty recognized the #hobbit as the first beings, a landmark case which opens the door for both the australasian #yowie and north american #bigfoot. china's stance on the @yeti is uncertain but they claim to have the most #smallfoot in the world. #fighttheman #gaia #metoo #endtheextinction #earthtoo #lgbqtc #cranesarepeopletoo #peta #seashepherd #christmas #origami #vegetablepower #vegetable
name: OG Crane Creaser

@regran_ed from @raindovemodel -  if the song â€œbaby itâ€™s cold outsideâ€ were a movie scene in modern day it could easily be a horror. the original intention of the song didnt mean to be sexist or sexual harassment. in 1946 it actually was just considered romantic for a love interest to not take no as an answer. to pursue no matter what and take what they wanted. however this sentiment and the lyrics havenâ€™t aged well. no means no means no. this attitude is not cute to replicate in modern day. 
so thatâ€™s why iâ€™ve launched a new series with @rosemcgowan called life as lyrics. we will be turning popular songs into movies scenes. we will remove the music and turn the lyrics into straight up dialogue. we want to address the fact that many of us have been lulled into being complicit towards the celebration of rape/violence/greed/selfishness/power abuse by masking the words with catchy beats. we donâ€™t need this kind of language to have good butt shake and head bob.

text:
do you know this situation? you are being attacked and the words build up in your head, swirl around, all those words, really good ones, strong ones, they travel down, sit on your tongue and - and then the one attacking you says something, something that hits you out of nowhere, punches you in your stomach and instead of all those amazing words the only thing that comes out are tears. before you know it you are crying. and people are staring. 
a colleague at university used the feedback opp during a seminar on solidarity (i was doing research on #metoo ) to demand of me to tell the class whether i had been assaulted or raped. or someone in my family or among my friends. it was a violation i had not expected. you might have guessed: i cried.

but also, i spoke up. i found strength in my tears. my vulnerability. i called him out, his misogynistic viewpoints and intrusive, violating behavior .
public tears are not a sign of weakness . and before you tell people to chill, not to overreact - consider their stories. i've shared mine (link in bio) and i'd love to hear your's! have you ever cried in public? found strength in tears? let's chat!

text:
[itâ€™s not pretty].
.
but this is the face of depression. no smiles or makeup here. this is what it looks like when your medication is being adjusted to adapt to your changing body. this is what it looks like when you cry because your heart hurts so much you have to take life second by second... not day by day.
.

but i am not alone. and i am not embarrassed. if i had a broken leg, there would be no shame in posting a picture of my cast. no one would get â€œfeelsâ€ from seeing that photo... they would just be curious as to the story behind the pain... how i ended up in a cast.
.
but the story behind this kind of pain is never asked. and thatâ€™s okay - for now - change takes time... but maybe we should work on that? ğŸ¤·ğŸ¼â€â™€ï¸ (p.s. iâ€™m *terrified* as to what the response of this post could be, but i believe the pros of vulnerability outweigh the cons of pretending.) #whatsthestorybehindthepain .
.
update: i have a tribe. yâ€™all! thank you for the comments, dms, texts, phone calls... i am amazed and so grateful for this group and the way you show up for me. and i am okay! just felt the need to be real and raw... thought maybe it could start a discussion. thank you again! ğŸ’œ.
.
update update: i am doing just fine! the intention of this post is let people know that they are not alone & and i am not embarrassed.

text:
these are my homemade, vegan, gluten free, sugar free, freaking delicious cupcakes. i am enjoying eating them even more today because i can taste a hint of justice with each and every bite i take. harvey weinstein is a predator and i am very relieved to see that the criminal case will be moving forward. me, and all my brave sisters who came forward over a year ago, did so to see justice served. we will speak and fight and do whatever it takes until that occurs. we are on the front lines of this fight. our stories and voices helped create a movement. countless brave voices have joined that chorus to change the world. never forget that the focus should be on the survivors and on changing society. and for those who have power and influence and a large platform, do not forget to elevate those who don't have the same access as you do. don't forget to elevate those who have sacrificed, to elevate those who have faced so many setbacks because of the actions of their abusers, to elevate those who truly need it. i fight for myself. i fight for my sisters. i fight for survivors everywhere. i fight for lasting change. we can all change this if we work together. the fight is far from over. .
.
.

text:
there are some ignorant people out there that automatically think suicide is â€œselfishâ€ or the â€œeasy way outâ€. the easy way out is to judge someone before understanding them. everyone is fighting an internal battle. some people get tired quicker then others and just want peace. they want the pain to stop. some people think that suicide is their only option because it is ignorant and poorly educated people who are so judgemental that it causes a person to carry on fighting on their own. who wants to be laughed at, put down or not understood by someone they love or care about when they finally admit they feel like giving up? i was so close to the permanent decision of ending everything because i thought that was my only option. i couldnâ€™t tell anyone. i only told one person how i felt, once, & i was told i was being stupid. after that i kept everything to myself. the stigma around suicide, mental health and abuse is upsetting. hopefully, one day, when someone does feel like they are ready to end their life, that they build up the courage to talk to someone. and instead of an ignorant and selfish reply of â€youâ€™re being stupidâ€, â€œyouâ€™re being selfishâ€ or â€œyouâ€™re taking the easy way outâ€, and the reply will be more empathic, comforting and will encourage that person to carry on because they are loved and wanted. 
if anyone is feeling like they are ready to end the battle... you are loved and you are wanted. keep going ğŸ˜˜

text:
this is one of the reasons i do what i do. why i made an oath to bettering myself, to holding myself accountable for what no longer serves me/ us, and continuing to stand up for what's right.

when we turn a blind's eye to our problems, it doesn't go away. when we deny that there's an issue, it doesn't go away. when we don't hold eachother accountable, it doesn't go away. so let's do something.

let's finally acknowledge eachother's pain. be better, be well. when we say, [insert passive aggression] "it's fine.", how are we inviting others to treat us? we are saying our pain is not worthy of acknowledgement, that we are not worthy. 
why do we deprive ourselves of love and comfort if we wouldn't do that to a child or an animal in pain? why do we do it to ourselves and eachother? toxic conditioning perhaps? (ie: "man up", "crying is for p*ssies", etc.).
â €â €
and where does that pain go if not outwards? it lingers, it simmers inwards.
â €â €
join me tomorrow evening (fri 12/21, 7 pm at @alignbrooklyn ) for yoga for a cause. acknowledging our shadows on the shortest day and longest night of the year. giving ourselves more, fulfilling our worth, and supporting others' in their healing. 100% of proceeds go to @rainn
â €â €â €
whether you're well on your journey or are trying to figure out what this means -
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â € i see you, i acknowledge you. ğŸ’— â €â €â €â €

a dozen years ago, tarana burke created the slogan, â€œme too.â€ burke, a bronx, n.y.-born african american civil rights activist, created the saying as a means to help women who had survived sexual violence.

years later, the hashtag â€œ#metooâ€ took off, initially without properly crediting burke.the movement also seemed initially to exclude women of color or, in the view of many, disproportionately focus on victimized white women â€“ prompting burke to passionately tell african american women earlier this year, â€œdonâ€™t opt yourself out of what was started for you because the media isnâ€™t acknowledging your hurt.â€ mostly white actresses in hollywood have become the public face of the movement and men like matt lauer, charlie rose, and les moonves have lost their high-profile jobs.

the success for proponents has been increasingly measured in terms of the career, stature, title or reputation loss experienced by the growing group of the (mostly men) accused in the media and a much smaller segment of accused that have been charged and/or convicted of crimes.
as some in the movement include bill cosbyâ€™s conviction on aggravated indecent assault charges as another consequence of #metoo, the pending charges and trial outcomes against movie mogul harvey weinstein remain unsettled.

cosbyâ€™s trials were so adversely impacted by media rhetoric and public perception that the inaccurate reporting of the actual substance was an unsworn-in additional witness against him â€” including a prosecutor who cited cosbyâ€™s conviction as a centerpiece of his election campaign.

in fact, even though videos have emerged of several professional football players and other celebrities assaulting physically assaulting women in hotel lobbies, elevators and hallways, cosby may ultimately find himself as the sole accused celebrity who serves actual prison time. text:
@regran_ed from @narcaway -  we all have a story. we all have a voice. we have been silenced for far too long by those who were inconvenienced by our truths.

own your story. we have never had so much support with social media, the times up and me too movements, and women (and men) finally speaking out.

i will not apologize if my story makes you uncomfortable, if you think it's inappropriate, or if you choose not to believe me.

i use instagram and youtube to share my experience. i tell my friends and family about the abuse i endured and ultimately survived.

i encourage you through your healing and recovery,  when you are ready, speak up, tell your story.  your voice was given to you to roar, and roar you will my lovely warriors!

text:
the figure represents a rise of 24% over five years, according to the office for national statistics.

these are the first official estimates of the number of deaths of homeless people, which show 84% of those who died were men.

#metoo you have a commodity you use readily as well abusively as well as being subjected to abuse and then positive discrimination.

where are all the mothers children aren't to save marriages? for xmas? because it was sunny, because i've met a load of homeless people who at hugely intelligent and thoughtful and giving when they have nothing to give.

nobody goes hungry, without shelter or laughing if i can help. god unwind my hands.

charities say the numbers confirm what they are seeing locally.

the ons figures show that there were 482 deaths among homeless people in 2013, rising to 597 in 2017. overall, an estimated 2,627 homeless people died during the five year period. a detailed breakdown shows:

more than half of the deaths were because of drug poisoning, liver disease or suicidedeaths increased throughout england but fell in waleslondon and north-west england had the highest proportion of deathsthe average age of death was 44 for men and 42 for women, compared with 76 for men and 81 for women among the rest of the population.

a cover up that pushes people to self destruct because persevering is more difficult. and then i am so angry when o see unhappy people taking their sh*t out on people already suffering.

at the wellspring charity for homeless and disadvantaged people in stockport, staff and volunteers have created a mural in remembrance of those who have died.

chief executive jonathan billings says he personally knows nine homeless people who have died in the past year alone.

he has worked there for 17 years and, while 10 years ago there might have been a few dozen people on the books, the numbers now run into hundreds - and more of them are dying.

the conservatives.

mark urmston, who visited the centre for some lunch, says his brother luke, 31, a rough sleeper, was found dead on a bench earlier this year after a suspected drugs overdose.

they were in and out of care as children, (hence the cover up, kill em)....

#repost from @inourhandsinitiative_ with @regram.app ... the #metoo movement has gained symbolic and international impact over time, and continues to build a strong support system for victims of gender based violence 
today, the lagos state ministry of women affairs and poverty alleviation in accordance with achieving the fifth goal of the sustainable development goal and in encouraging the rising wave of the #metoo movement in nigeria, organized an impact walk to sensitize and encourage more nigerians to speak up and further take action against gender based violence.

our team was honoured to be invited as part of this impactful walk and collaboration.

at in our hands initiative we remain committed to taking action against all forms of gender based violence in nigeria, and the world over; beyond this walk, we pledge our continuous solidarity to support the elimination of all forms of violence against every individual.

#standup #speakup 
#breakthesilence #meetoo #notogenderbasedviolenceinnigeria #heforshe #timesup

we're thrilled to announce that melissa mark-viverito @mmviverito will be speaking at ignite's young women run new york conference on january 26, 2019, in brooklyn, new york. as the former speaker of the new york city council and candidate for public advocate for the city of new york, she has a wealth of information to share with you - the next generation of leaders. join us at #ywrnewyork (link in bio!) and hear first-hand from melissa mark-viverito about why she was called to serve and how you can learn from her experience in elected office and on the campaign trail.
.
.
.

text:
this is a book from my first giveaway win! it was recently sent to me by laci from @bookpairings! (thanks, laci!) those who knew follows a woman named lena, who suspects the popular senator she dated back in college is taking advantage of the woman who is now introducing him at rallies. when the woman ends up dead, lena finds herself haunted by her past with the senator and the violent incident that ended their relationship. did he kill the woman?
.
this book was filled with suspense and moved through time fluidly. the writing style was also really refreshing. it was broken into very short chapters with scenes from plays in between. it also covered heavy but important topics of sexual harassment and abuse, celebrating those with resilience and the courage to sacrifice everything. 4/5ğŸŒŸ

text:
a dozen years ago, tarana burke created the slogan, â€œme too.â€ burke, a bronx, n.y.-born african american civil rights activist, created the saying as a means to help women who had survived sexual violence.

years later, the hashtag â€œ#metooâ€ took off, initially without properly crediting burke.the movement also seemed initially to exclude women of color or, in the view of many, disproportionately focus on victimized white women â€“ prompting burke to passionately tell african american women earlier this year, â€œdonâ€™t opt yourself out of what was started for you because the media isnâ€™t acknowledging your hurt.â€ mostly white actresses in hollywood have become the public face of the movement and men like matt lauer, charlie rose, and les moonves have lost their high-profile jobs.

the success for proponents has been increasingly measured in terms of the career, stature, title or reputation loss experienced by the growing group of the (mostly men) accused in the media and a much smaller segment of accused that have been charged and/or convicted of crimes.
as some in the movement include bill cosbyâ€™s conviction on aggravated indecent assault charges as another consequence of #metoo, the pending charges and trial outcomes against movie mogul harvey weinstein remain unsettled.

cosbyâ€™s trials were so adversely impacted by media rhetoric and public perception that the inaccurate reporting of the actual substance was an unsworn-in additional witness against him â€” including a prosecutor who cited cosbyâ€™s conviction as a centerpiece of his election campaign.

in fact, even though videos have emerged of several professional football players and other celebrities assaulting physically assaulting women in hotel lobbies, elevators and hallways, cosby may ultimately find himself as the sole accused celebrity who serves actual prison time. (continue article in comment section)

"being 19 and a receptionist in a huge construction company has been interesting. iâ€™ve had people ask me â€˜how many online shops have you looked at today?â€™, or told me â€˜youâ€™re pretty, itâ€™s nice for the boysâ€™. when my colleague and i were decorating our christmas tree, she was reaching to put the star on the top and someone said â€˜youâ€™re going to need a longer skirt for thatâ€™. itâ€™s been very belittling but also made me feel guilty, as though iâ€™ve got some kind of pretty privilege.
.
i feel like iâ€™m constantly learning more and changing my view towards all things feminism, which has made this really hard to write. there are a million and one expectations placed upon women: to be sexy and hot, and to be strong and empowered, when all i really want is the choice, and for that choice to really be mine. and despite how frustrating and rubbish it is give ignorant people the benefit of the doubt and explain a different perspective to them, it can often be worth it." â€” anna-lucy ğŸ’ƒ

learn more about fov online at csindy.com and indygive.com! . . . .

hello to my favorite community, and the hundreds of new faces that joined in yesterday (wow!!) iâ€™m thrilled to have you here and wanted to say hi! ğŸ‘‹ğŸ» â£
â£
my name is jules and iâ€™m a life coach specializing in intimacy and spiritual wellness. what does that mean? i help people get crystal clear about their love for themselves. we do that by seeing you, together, including the parts that got buried deep down inside of you when you were hurt, and then we set it all free. it feels so good to find that we are free and loved and cherished after we have felt our most challenging pain. it is my honor to walk that path with others.â£
â£
a few years ago i was in transition brought on by trauma that shook me awake to my deepest love. my daughter was born scary-early and got dangerously sick. when we brought her home after months in the hospital, nothing seemed like it worked anymore: my friends, my beliefs, my church, my marriage, my body, my identity... everything felt confusing and painful. i realized i needed the freedom that could only come from vulnerable, relentless, all-out self acceptance. so i went within and i learned from the love i found there. i created tools and practices for myself that i started sharing with others and thatâ€™s how my coaching practice was born. â£
â£
i love sharing my story in this space more than anything else, and want you to know that here, you are invited, and welcomed to be vulnerably you. we do not strive for perfection here. we strive to be all of who we are. i am a mom of two. i help people heal. iâ€™ve learned that making all of that look perfect is not what makes me happy. authenticity is what makes me happy, and i can only have that if i am living fully as me. mistakes and all.â£
â£
i lose my patience.â£
i disappoint my partner.â£
i work hard to be an expert at what i do and i still feel uninspired some days.â£
the goal isnt perfect.â£
i hate perfect.â£
i let go of perfect years ago.â£
the goal is to do all of this:â£
the mistakesâ£
the dreamingâ£
the apologizingâ£
the learningâ£
the teachingâ£
the healingâ£
the relationshipsâ£
as myself.â£
â£

text:
this poem is from my poetry book, 21 & no fun, itâ€™s about the lunch i had with my abuser a year after weâ€™d separated. i was nineteen, still working for his sister, and still not fully able to swallow that he had abused me. the moment i got up to go to the bathroom and looked in the mirror was vital. sometimes, when you go back home to your parents or hang out with old friends, your brain tricks you into thinking youâ€™ve time traveled. heâ€™d walked all over me, and when i looked in the mirror, i was genuinely shocked to see myself. i had chopped off all my hair, dyed it bright pink. i was nineteen, and i was openly queer, and i was beginning to figure out the kind of of person i wanted to be. being around my abuser had made me forget all that, in an instant. that moment, when i stared at myself in the mirror and came back to myself, was the start of realizing the truth. i had been the victim of abuse. 
last year, in the midst of writing this poetry book, i reported him to the church weâ€™d met at. this was huge. his sister blocked me on every platform, cutting me off from children i had helped raise up until that point. there were other consequences, ones that cut too deep and are still lingering, but i was set free by reporting him. 
the nightmares havenâ€™t fully stopped, but theyâ€™re less frightening. the anger isnâ€™t always kept at bay. the unfairness of the situation hits me all the time. but i no longer keep his secret. i no longer let him have the power to make me forget who i am. 
i had the courage to do this because of poetry, because of the metoo movement, and because it was time. this poem means so much to me, because it was writing down this moment that helped me move forward.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
the crucible_abigail williams 
happy #monologuethrsday everyone! the monologue of today is another excerpt from the crucible by arthur miller, and it's the scene in which abigail, in a few lines, shows all her true colors: a passive aggressive little coward, who has no scruples in using lies and deceit to protect herself manipulating the others and blaming a crime that never really happened on the weakest one so to protect herself from her own actions.
lies and deceit, passive aggressiveness, and hysteria, that's the world of the crucible, and what i like of this play is that it exposes how, at the end of the day, more that the tyrants, our real enemies are those weak miserable cowards who decide to serve and protect the injustice and sell their brothers and sisters out, just like that.
but it's their value that's less than zero. stay valuable.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
hey hey, little girl |  not the words i get so much as the words that lurk behind what happens.
*
i was rather awkwardly filling up on water at a sink behind a chevron in la quinta, ca when the guy at the counter â€” a kind man in his late thirties, maybe, about my age â€” asked me what i was doing; i suppose people donâ€™t often come around there trying to fill up on water. i said i was drydocking outside of joshua tree while exploring the park for a week or two. as he helped me load my gallon jugs into the back of my van, he asked if i was doing that by myself. i said yes. â€œyouâ€™re a brave woman,â€ he said.
*
i know iâ€™m not the only one who wishes i lived in a world where a comment like that would not only be inapplicable but untrue; a world where a woman of any age could travel and explore wild places alone and not worry about her safety. in my most leisurely moments iâ€™m still dogged by the awareness that i need to be careful. as someone who can be overly trusting, i use my spidey sense in conversations with new people. i lock everything up. i use my peripheral vision in parking lots and rarely go out at night. but ever since that comment at the chevron i second-guess myself whenever iâ€™m asked if iâ€™m on my own, the replies running their permutations in my head:
- yes i am.
- yes i am and go away, fucktard.
- no, my partnerâ€™s just out taking the dog for a run. (hopefully theyâ€™ve noticed the two large pairs of menâ€™s boots and giant metal bowl iâ€™ve set outside in hopes of keeping them and other fucktards away from my little camp)?
*
tbh i donâ€™t actually have menâ€™s boots or a giant metal bowl to keep fucktards away from my little campâ€¦
*
but over nine months i can still count on one hand the number of times iâ€™ve dealt with unsavory types who creeped me out, so i think iâ€™m doing okay. i wish more women didnâ€™t think that what iâ€™m doing is daring or unusual or exceptionally brave. i have a growing community of people i can rely on throughout the desert southwest who have given me the world alreadyâ€¦so that when a fucktard comes up and asks if iâ€™m on my own, i can say â€œno, iâ€™m with my friends, theyâ€™re camped right over thereâ€...and that would be the truth. â€¢

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin

bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with ficial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

breaking through the trap of poverty until she finished writing her first book of the harry potter series, jk rowling was the first author in the world to reach a net worth of $1 billion. 
her determination fueled her to continue writing as a child & into her adulthood, even when she failed or was overwhelmed by grief to overcome her inner demons. 
sanfe salutes her spirit to inspire an entire generation to read and her fierce ambition & activism regarding anything from politics to literature.

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

.

.

text:
anyone who consumes dairy means this baby isn't. somewhere a mother's milk, rightfully belongs to this angel who was taken from her mother. one of the most sacred relationships, a mother and child.. broken. so we can steal the milk that doesn't belong to us. ever wonder why so many people are sick with numerous ailments and diseases because of dairy? it's simple - #notyourmomnotyourmilk. .

@regran_ed ğŸ‘‰ @earthlove777 - ğŸ’”rp @dxepriya when i reached inside of this baby calf's hutch, what i saw broke me. she was covered in diarrhea, which for calves can be extremely deadly. her filthy hutch had no bedding, no water, and no food. the only thing she could call her own is the ear-tag that was forcibly pierced into her ear when she was just a few days old. but the most haunting part of this experience was how lonely she was.
her loneliness is a routine practice in the dairy industry which depends on separating mothers from their babies. when julianne, alicia and i found angel at raymar ranch, she too was separated from her mom. but not only that, angel was thrown away like trash in a graveyard, waiting to die.

when i tried to help angel, she was ripped away from my arms. why is it that the industry sees us helping animals, their response is to punish us? it's because the truth is so scary that they feel it's criminal to publicize it.

if animal rights activists are considered criminals for trying to save baby cows from a life of misery and loneliness, we need more, not less of us. #dairyfree #dairy #govegan #crueltyfree #meat #hamburger #burger #pizzahut #pizzapizza #ilovepizza #cheesecake #cheesecakefactory #cheesey #cheeseboard #creamy #cream #creamcheese #dairyisscary #stopseparatingfamilies #burgerking #tacobell #burrito #quesadilla #vegano #metoo #donttakeourplanetforgranted- #breastfeeding #breastmilk

text:
[1.3] every story has two sides. in our play, they go by the names marilyn and norma jeane. love is blonde is a story about the conflict between two women who are really just one complex soul. marilyn is the american icon, the myth, the bombshell who squints her eyes whilst sipping stardom and fame. norma jeane is the ordinary girl with a dream to become an actress, who looks at the world with hesitant, big eyes and a want to be loved for her normal self.

ultimately, the duality that runs in marilyn and norma jeaneâ€™s veins is the inner battle every woman fights to find her true self.
_______________

from the script of love is blonde:
norma: i hate you, marilyn monroe, i hate you! i did not want it to come to this! 
marilyn: if you really didn't want this, then why did you never stop me? am i too smart for you? or are you just a failure? you'd be nothing without me. i brought glory and power, when you only had misery and sadness. 
norma: you sold our soul to the devil. 
marilyn: what choice did we have? 
norma: now i regret never having had a normal life.
_______________

our #crowdfunding is ending in a few hours on the #linkinbio. thanks to your generosity, we have raised 38,280$ and pushed over our goal. you are amazing, and we are sincerely humbled by your support.

text:
if you grow up being treated as if you are worthy of and the cause for cruelty and banishment, you will seek relationships that affirm that.  if you are raised to feel valued and connected, you will seek relationships that affirm that.  those become our core guiding beliefs about our â€œselvesâ€ and connection. 
my sister and i lived two different experiences.  my motherâ€™s approval and endorsement of her, as clear evidence of fine mothering, connected my sister to the rest of the family.  my motherâ€™s experience with me was used to divide me from them. one of us got a bridge and one got a stonewall.  on my less difficult days, i was sometimes treated kind of like the sick mangey dogs roaming the streets in south east asia. i recall badly wanting to hold them tightly and whisper â€œit will be okâ€. but i was afraid and that was a lie(it would never be ok), so i would pet them with a smooth stick or a piece of trash and offer them scraps of food.  it made me feel both sad and like an asshole because i recognized that more was needed and deserved(...)
a wise friend shared with me that â€œdifficult children are here to wake their parents.  but your mother was not interestedâ€. it is true, she showed reflexive aversion to or dismissal of anything/anyone which/whom was not emotionally simple and intellectually stimulating.  i have been anything but those.

text:
follow my facebook page!!
advocate ashley

it's my own kind of personal blog where i write about my struggles and triumphs, i laugh and act silly, sometimes i'll write and be crying

but its real!! some of my stories are hard to read, some have very sensitive content, some of them may make you mad, or sad, but all of my stories are 100% raw truth. i won't sugar coat anything, i'll write it exactly how things happened, how i felt, and what was said.
my goal is to show people they aren't alone, yeah i know, everyone's doing that, but i don't think anyone is as open, or as honest, or as genuine as i will be, i find people are too "nice" about things. 
well. not. me.
come see for yourself!

i'll write about growing up in poverty, domestic abuse, friendships, relationships, loss, gains, school, bills, everything in life that essentially pisses you off. ğŸ˜‹

own your story. we have never had so much support with social media, the times up and me too movements, and women (and men) finally speaking out.

i will not apologize if my story makes you uncomfortable, if you think it's inappropriate, or if you choose not to believe me.

i use instagram and youtube to share my experience. i tell my friends and family about the abuse i endured and ultimately survived.

i encourage you through your healing and recovery,  when you are ready, speak up, tell your story.  your voice was given to you to roar, and roar you will my lovely warriors!

text:
thereâ€™s a lot of power in the written word.  itâ€™s helped me through loss, grief, working through big decisions, documenting life changing experiences and expressing my inner most thoughts, dreams and goals. 
itâ€™s amazing to go back a year or two and see how far youâ€™ve progressed.  in our day to day life we may not see how far weâ€™ve come.  once you see it in writing you acknowledge your growth and it will fuel you to keep going.  when i reflect back, iâ€™m amazed that the exact goals i wrote for myself, i accomplished or am now working towards. 
just like the power of positive thinking, thereâ€™s the power of positive writing.  if youâ€™re already journaling, good for you! 
if not, i encourage you to just start simple by writing 2-3 things that youâ€™re grateful for and 2-3 things you would like to accomplish each day and see what gems of wisdom and positivity emerge.  xo  #youglowgirl

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the companyâ€™s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when youâ€™re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a personâ€™s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the â€œtraining setâ€ refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your â€œfeature setâ€: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, itâ€™s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data â€“ the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that youâ€™re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the companyâ€™s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when youâ€™re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a personâ€™s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the â€œtraining setâ€ refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your â€œfeature setâ€: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, itâ€™s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data â€“ the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that youâ€™re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the companyâ€™s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when youâ€™re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a personâ€™s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the â€œtraining setâ€ refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your â€œfeature setâ€: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, itâ€™s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data â€“ the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that youâ€™re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
anonymous content teams with red arrow & charlie lyons to adapt joanne lipmanâ€™s â€˜thatâ€™s what she saidâ€™ for tv
#anonymous content #breaking news #charlie lyons #joanne lipman #news #red arrow studios international #that's what she said
anonymous content has teamed up with red arrow studios international and air force one producer charlie lyons to adapt joanne lipmanâ€™s book thatâ€™s what she said: what men need to know (and women need to tell them) about working together into a scripted tv series. the global arm of the german commercial broadcaster prosiebensat.1 has optioned the rights to the book from the former usa today editor. it combines anecdotes from lipmanâ€™s own rise to the top of a male-dominated industry with data and research to offer real-world solutions for combatingÂ unconscious bias, sexual harassment,Â  mansplaining, the gender wage gap, and other systemic problems people confront daily in professional environments. the true detective producer will co-produce with red arrow studios international and lyons with the latter exec producing alongside paul green, paula munoz vega, carlo dusi and bo stehmeier. they are currently in discussions with writers to develop.Â thatâ€™s what she said was published by harpercollins earlier this year. carlo dusi, evp commercial strategy, scripted, red arrow studios international, said, â€œjoanneâ€™s work is timely and insightful, offering a nuanced exploration of gender politics in the workplace and how we can collectively progress in the wake of #metoo. weâ€™re excited to be working with charlie and anonymous content to develop what promises to be a smart and engaging piece of television.â€ lyons added, â€œjoanne is a dazzling storyteller with the worldview and wisdom to tackle this provocative project. iâ€™m honored to work with her, anonymous and red arrow on this exciting television event.â€

"hil egiten gaituzte. emakumeak garelako  hil egiten gaituzte. ez, ez dute inor hiltzen parke ilunean bakarrik ibiltzeagatik edo gauez korrika egiteagatik. ez. motiboa beti da bera: emakumeak izateagatik hiltzen gaituzte. patriarkatu honek, bere aliatu ekonomiko eta politikoak lagun, emakumeak izate hutsagatik hiltzen gaitu. gu gara pausoa azkartzen dugunak, gu eskuetan dardara igartzen dugunak, gu etxerako bidean laguntza eskatzen dugunak. gu, emakumeok: eta larritu egiten gara, emakume izate hutsagatik hilgarriak garelako."

text:
*trigger warning*
you are a survivor
in every sense of the word
unrelenting,
you have time and time again
returned from the depths of hell
covered it the black smudge of a society
plagued by impunity
yet,
while your lungs are filled with the smoke of blame and shame
you are still here
fighting to live
fighting to love
fighting to heal
and every time your eyes flutter open in the early wake of dusk
your heart beats together
in time with the beating of millions of surviving hearts
a noise so loud
it echoes and booms
sending chills down the spines of the sleeping beasts behind enemy lines
we are survivors
and we will win this war
together
just wait and see
(original art & poem)

text:
dear sonu nigam i read your interview, 
1. to define me basis a relationship with another person & not as an individual, going to the extension of memory loss for my name; a gift of patriarchal conditioning. 
2. to refer to my opinions & stand in the #metoo movement as â€˜vomitingâ€™; bad taste. 
3. to defend a known serial sexual offender like anu malik, thereby discrediting all the women who have called him out; disturbing, horrifying & heartbreaking. 
4. to back track on your own statements made on a professional forum after a few hours & refer to some statements as a â€˜jokeâ€™ & others as something else; confusing? 
5. to hide under bluster, male ego & pettiness; unbefitting. 
6. sonu jee, is all the above an indication of someone maintaining decorum & grace? a showcase of your peace loving & non-quarrelsome nature? (your claims in the interview). does all this befit your senior & legend status? worthy legacy to leave behind for your admirers, fans & followers? 
7. i refuse to call you someoneâ€™s papa or someoneâ€™s husband or someoneâ€™s son. you are yet for me one of the greatest classic film singers of india & someone i have found to be particularly nice to me every time weâ€™ve met for close to a decade & half. in personal & professional settings. that you found no other means of experiencing me as a person  despite knowing me for over a decade, but as a â€˜wifeâ€™, speaks volumes, of your conditioning & world view. 
8. i wish you & your family well, but unlike you, i will not â€˜defendâ€™ or behave with anyone in a particular manner  basis a personal â€˜relationshipâ€™. we occupy a public space as artists & it is my duty to stand for what is right. glad you value your relationship with my partner ram sampath with whom you have not only sung songs like dil dooba in khakhee but others over the years. i do not occupy a position of power in your eyes for you to value my worth. know one thing though, not all relationships are basis, give & take. some are basis a shared value & belief system. we possibly have none, unfortunate. (part i)

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
this is my life, before what happened to me, and especially now. i didnâ€™t ask to be attacked. i didnâ€™t ask for nightmares that wake me up even after taking sleeping medication. i didnâ€™t ask for the weight of flashbacks to hold me down and prevent me from participating in day to day life. the debilitating panic attacks that constantly bombard my body. constantly tense. learning new triggers. feeling so different from everyone, feeling like iâ€™m either being judged or pitied. feeling guilty when i ask for help. i sometimes feel like people think iâ€™m bragging or i talk too much about it, but i donâ€™t know anyone who would brag about something that destroys your quality of life, and talking about it lets others understand how to help. 
i canâ€™t work now. my heart hurts and i know iâ€™m not feeling better, but i wake up every day and try. thats the beauty of nature. fighting to live when your mind is trying to kill you. iâ€™m trying to get better, but some things just take time. 
vaping is even a slight trigger now, because i was vaping (as usual) when i was attacked. i refuse to let him win though, vaping is my life, so i vape anyways because i wonâ€™t let something i love be taken from me over a horrible human beings actions. 
#ptsd#ptsdawareness#nightmares#anxiety#depression#survivor#mentalhealthawareness#metoo#womenarestrong#keepfighting#warrior#onedayatatime

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
africa has the highest prevalence rate of sexual abuse.
.
.
findings from a national survey  on violence against children in nigeria confirmed one in four females reported experiencing sexual violence in childhood with approximately 70% reporting more than one incident of sexual violence. .
.
.
in the same study, it was found that 24.8% of femalesâ€™ ages 18 to 24 years experienced sexual abuse prior to age 18 of which 5.0% sought help with only 3.5% receiving any services .
.
violence against women and girls is a complete violation of human rights. .
.
the 2030 agenda promises to put an end to barriers that prevent women and girls from realising their full potential. let's join hands together to stop domestic violence, sexual abuse and rape. .
.
.
.
